ce:section.ce:para:
The relaxation rates were calculated for each carbonic acid conjugate anion and averaged by pH-dependent distribution to yield theoretical relaxation rates. The intramolecular and hydration-water dipolar distance of 1H-13C and the carbonic-acid-conjugate-anions-to-GQD particle radius, derived from the rotational correlation time of the particle, were least-square fitted to give the closest match to the observed relaxation rates (Table 3
                      and Fig. 4
                     ). The anisotropic rotational reorientation that describes the non-rigidity of hydration water was not considered, as it would further increase the number of required fitting parameters [35]. The relaxation rates were fitted, as indicated, to single distances. Because the relaxation rates are inversely proportional to the sixth order of distance, if multiple distances are present, they are interpreted as the corresponding average.
